WEBVTT

00:00:00.031 --> 00:00:04.416
SPEAKER_00: At T plus 0.678 seconds, the first warning appeared.

00:00:05.378 --> 00:00:10.205
SPEAKER_00: It was smoke from the aft field joint of Challenger's right solid rocket booster.

00:00:11.205 --> 00:00:14.631
SPEAKER_00: More smoke followed through the first two and a half seconds of flight.

00:00:15.631 --> 00:00:16.373
SPEAKER_00: Then it stopped.

00:00:17.574 --> 00:00:20.518
SPEAKER_00: For the next minute, Challenger looked like a launch.

00:00:21.379 --> 00:00:22.361
SPEAKER_00: The vehicle climbed.

00:00:23.001 --> 00:00:24.925
SPEAKER_00: The call-outs continued.

00:00:24.989 --> 00:00:31.079
SPEAKER_00: The machinery of the mission appeared to be doing what it had done before, but the accident had already begun.

00:00:31.120 --> 00:00:37.790
SPEAKER_00: The visible catastrophe came later, about 73 seconds after liftoff.

00:00:37.811 --> 00:00:40.536
SPEAKER_00: By then, the public story could be told quickly.

00:00:40.555 --> 00:00:45.984
SPEAKER_00: It was cold, the O-rings failed, and seven crew members died.

00:00:45.965 --> 00:00:47.207
SPEAKER_00: That version is accurate.

00:00:47.889 --> 00:00:50.673
SPEAKER_00: It is also too small to explain why launch was still allowed.

00:00:51.395 --> 00:00:57.064
SPEAKER_00: The smoke is the better starting point, because it separates the consequence from the beginning.

00:00:58.006 --> 00:01:01.112
SPEAKER_00: At 73 seconds, the chain became public.

00:01:01.893 --> 00:01:05.000
SPEAKER_00: At less than one second, the chain became physical.

00:01:05.840 --> 00:01:09.507
SPEAKER_00: Before that, the chain had already been organizational.

00:01:09.487 --> 00:01:11.731
SPEAKER_00: The harder question starts before ignition.

00:01:12.513 --> 00:01:24.093
SPEAKER_00: How does a warning stay visible in records, inspections, memos, charts, and meetings, then arrive at the final decision too weak to stop the machine?

00:01:25.236 --> 00:01:29.403
SPEAKER_00: Challenger did not fail because the danger was invisible.

00:01:29.384 --> 00:01:36.697
SPEAKER_00: The Rogers Commission identified the physical failure, the joint between the two lower segments of the right solid rocket motor.

00:01:37.558 --> 00:01:41.546
SPEAKER_00: The seals in that joint were supposed to keep hot combustion gases inside the booster.

00:01:42.387 --> 00:01:42.948
SPEAKER_00: They did not.

00:01:43.870 --> 00:01:44.590
SPEAKER_00: Cold mattered.

00:01:45.332 --> 00:01:51.543
SPEAKER_00: The launch temperature was 36 degrees Fahrenheit, far below previous shuttle launch experience.

00:01:51.659 --> 00:02:00.572
SPEAKER_00: At the coldest point on the right aft field joint, the temperature was estimated at 28 degrees Fahrenheit, plus or minus 5 degrees.

00:02:00.890 --> 00:02:02.712
SPEAKER_00: Rubber behaves differently in cold.

00:02:03.593 --> 00:02:08.418
SPEAKER_00: A seal that responds quickly when warm can respond more slowly when cold.

00:02:09.379 --> 00:02:11.762
SPEAKER_00: In this joint, timing was not a detail.

00:02:12.323 --> 00:02:13.463
SPEAKER_00: It was the safety margin.

00:02:14.185 --> 00:02:18.490
SPEAKER_00: The O-ring story is true, but the launch decision came from a system.

00:02:19.330 --> 00:02:22.274
SPEAKER_00: That system had seen O-ring damage before.

00:02:23.055 --> 00:02:23.975
SPEAKER_00: It had paperwork.

00:02:24.657 --> 00:02:26.778
SPEAKER_00: It had engineers raising concerns.

00:02:27.247 --> 00:02:31.997
SPEAKER_00: It had a recommendation from the contractor not to launch below 53 degrees Fahrenheit.

00:02:32.997 --> 00:02:35.042
SPEAKER_00: It had managers who challenged the data.

00:02:35.081 --> 00:02:40.091
SPEAKER_00: It had safety structures that were supposed to give danger a stronger voice.

00:02:41.052 --> 00:02:42.996
SPEAKER_00: The pattern is warning softening.

00:02:44.078 --> 00:02:48.986
SPEAKER_00: Evidence stayed visible while each pass-through process made launch easier to defend.

00:02:49.793 --> 00:02:52.979
SPEAKER_00: The clean version of the story asks why a seal failed in the cold.

00:02:53.719 --> 00:03:02.335
SPEAKER_00: The harder version asks why the system was still willing to rely on that seal in those conditions, after years of evidence that the joint was not behaving as expected.

00:03:03.497 --> 00:03:07.784
SPEAKER_00: The solid rocket boosters were built from large cylindrical segments.

00:03:07.764 --> 00:03:12.973
SPEAKER_00: Those segments had to be joined, and the joints had to contain the pressure and heat of ignition.

00:03:13.915 --> 00:03:18.143
SPEAKER_00: The failed joint was an aft field joint on the right solid rocket motor.

00:03:19.064 --> 00:03:24.574
SPEAKER_00: It used a tang and clevis design, with a primary O-ring and a secondary O-ring.

00:03:25.336 --> 00:03:27.659
SPEAKER_00: The primary seal was supposed to do the work.

00:03:28.401 --> 00:03:31.325
SPEAKER_00: The secondary seal was supposed to be backup.

00:03:31.306 --> 00:03:34.550
SPEAKER_00: That sounds redundant until the timing problem becomes clear.

00:03:35.633 --> 00:03:38.997
SPEAKER_00: At ignition, pressure inside the booster rises fast.

00:03:39.860 --> 00:03:40.980
SPEAKER_00: The metal parts move.

00:03:41.703 --> 00:03:44.006
SPEAKER_00: The gap between tang and clevis can open.

00:03:44.766 --> 00:03:48.552
SPEAKER_00: The O-ring has to respond while that geometry is changing.

00:03:49.375 --> 00:03:55.204
SPEAKER_00: It has to move into place quickly enough to block hot gas before the gas reaches the seal path.

00:03:55.183 --> 00:03:56.825
SPEAKER_00: The design did include a seal.

00:03:57.687 --> 00:04:00.870
SPEAKER_00: The hard part was that the seal had to work during a violent transition.

00:04:01.631 --> 00:04:02.752
SPEAKER_00: Pressure was rising.

00:04:03.513 --> 00:04:04.854
SPEAKER_00: The joint was changing shape.

00:04:05.514 --> 00:04:09.538
SPEAKER_00: The rubber had to follow the metal quickly enough to keep combustion gas inside the motor.

00:04:10.340 --> 00:04:13.963
SPEAKER_00: The commission found that cold reduced O-ring resiliency.

00:04:14.745 --> 00:04:21.732
SPEAKER_00: A compressed O-ring at 75 degrees Fahrenheit could return toward its shape far faster than one at 30 degrees Fahrenheit.

00:04:21.711 --> 00:04:27.420
SPEAKER_00: Challenger's right aft field joint was not merely cold in the ordinary sense.

00:04:28.281 --> 00:04:33.588
SPEAKER_00: It was estimated near 28 degrees Fahrenheit, with a 5 degree uncertainty on either side.

00:04:34.589 --> 00:04:36.252
SPEAKER_00: The seal did not need to disappear.

00:04:37.033 --> 00:04:38.115
SPEAKER_00: It only needed to be late.

00:04:38.875 --> 00:04:43.843
SPEAKER_00: The exact temperature matters, because cold can sound like background weather.

00:04:44.783 --> 00:04:47.668
SPEAKER_00: Here, cold was part of the mechanism.

00:04:47.648 --> 00:04:53.314
SPEAKER_00: It changed the response time of a part that was already being asked to seal while the joint was opening.

00:04:54.334 --> 00:04:59.800
SPEAKER_00: That timing problem matters because it connects the physical failure to the organizational one.

00:05:00.901 --> 00:05:05.064
SPEAKER_00: The hardware needed to respond before combustion escaped the joint.

00:05:06.086 --> 00:05:09.850
SPEAKER_00: The organization needed to respond before repeated evidence became routine.

00:05:10.930 --> 00:05:14.634
SPEAKER_00: The joint problem was not discovered cleanly after the disaster.

00:05:15.964 --> 00:05:37.973
SPEAKER_00: commission traced a history tests and flights had shown o-ring damage hot gases were not supposed to touch the o-rings yet flight experience showed that the seal system was not behaving with the margin the program wanted to believe it had sts2 was an early receipt after that flight

00:05:38.105 --> 00:05:43.754
SPEAKER_00: Inspection found primary O-ring erosion in the right solid rocket booster aft field joint.

00:05:44.595 --> 00:05:48.360
SPEAKER_00: Hot motor gas had reached a seal that was supposed to be protected from it.

00:05:49.302 --> 00:05:51.406
SPEAKER_00: That should have carried force.

00:05:51.425 --> 00:05:56.995
SPEAKER_00: Instead, the anomaly did not reach the Level 1 Flight Readiness Review for STS-3.

00:05:58.055 --> 00:06:04.146
SPEAKER_00: It was not tracked in the Marshall Problem Assessment System in the way the later record would make necessary.

00:06:04.413 --> 00:06:07.958
SPEAKER_00: The warning existed at a level where the system could continue.

00:06:08.858 --> 00:06:11.622
SPEAKER_00: The program also had criticality language.

00:06:11.642 --> 00:06:21.415
SPEAKER_00: The field joint seal had been treated as redundant, then later shifted after the secondary O-ring could no longer be assumed to provide reliable backup under all conditions.

00:06:22.817 --> 00:06:25.742
SPEAKER_00: The administrative label changed, but flight continued.

00:06:26.723 --> 00:06:28.125
SPEAKER_00: That paperwork trail matters.

00:06:28.966 --> 00:06:31.769
SPEAKER_00: The system had a way to name catastrophic risk.

00:06:32.088 --> 00:06:35.451
SPEAKER_00: It had a way to say that a failure could mean loss of vehicle and crew.

00:06:36.372 --> 00:06:43.759
SPEAKER_00: But naming criticality did not automatically force the launch process to behave as if every warning around that part was critical.

00:06:44.819 --> 00:06:47.762
SPEAKER_00: The label and the practice began to separate.

00:06:47.802 --> 00:06:50.886
SPEAKER_00: The paperwork made the danger more visible.

00:06:51.666 --> 00:06:53.829
SPEAKER_00: The launch process still made it manageable.

00:06:55.170 --> 00:07:01.757
SPEAKER_00: A technical fact can be documented accurately and still fail to become a launch-stopping fact.

00:07:02.259 --> 00:07:05.903
SPEAKER_00: In the shuttle program, repeated damage should have sharpened attention.

00:07:06.824 --> 00:07:10.187
SPEAKER_00: Repeated survival also created a dangerous kind of confidence.

00:07:11.307 --> 00:07:14.071
SPEAKER_00: STS-51C increased concern.

00:07:14.891 --> 00:07:20.016
SPEAKER_00: The flight showed hot gas past the primary O-ring, and low temperature was part of the discussion.

00:07:20.916 --> 00:07:25.380
SPEAKER_00: Theokol concluded that the condition was not desirable but acceptable.

00:07:26.302 --> 00:07:28.704
SPEAKER_00: That phrase matters because it sounds disciplined.

00:07:29.464 --> 00:07:31.947
SPEAKER_00: It sounds like risk has been bounded.

00:07:32.011 --> 00:07:38.218
SPEAKER_00: But if the boundary is wrong, the phrase becomes a way to keep flying with a condition that should be getting harder to accept.

00:07:39.220 --> 00:07:43.865
SPEAKER_00: Then came S-T-S-51-B.

00:07:44.987 --> 00:07:49.252
SPEAKER_00: After primary O-ring erosion, a launch constraint was placed.

00:07:49.954 --> 00:07:52.598
SPEAKER_00: A launch constraint should be a hard object in the path.

00:07:53.218 --> 00:07:55.982
SPEAKER_00: It should say, resolve this before flight.

00:07:56.723 --> 00:08:01.949
SPEAKER_00: But the constraint was waived for later flights, including the path toward 51L.

00:08:03.127 --> 00:08:06.012
SPEAKER_00: That is where formal safety language can become misleading.

00:08:07.012 --> 00:08:11.879
SPEAKER_00: The record can still say constraint, while the operating habit says waiver.

00:08:12.940 --> 00:08:17.226
SPEAKER_00: Once a constraint has been waived, the next waiver is easier to imagine.

00:08:17.968 --> 00:08:21.593
SPEAKER_00: The first exception becomes part of the experience base.

00:08:21.572 --> 00:08:24.519
SPEAKER_00: Each waiver changed the practical meaning of the constraint.

00:08:25.321 --> 00:08:26.923
SPEAKER_00: The words still existed.

00:08:26.983 --> 00:08:29.048
SPEAKER_00: The stopping power weakened.

00:08:29.750 --> 00:08:34.299
SPEAKER_00: The constraint history also keeps the story from becoming one bad meeting.

00:08:34.432 --> 00:08:38.136
SPEAKER_00: the system had already built a way to keep the joint issue compatible with flight.

00:08:39.158 --> 00:08:43.844
SPEAKER_00: By the time January 27th arrived, launch was not pushing against a fresh warning.

00:08:44.585 --> 00:08:48.190
SPEAKER_00: It was pushing against a warning that had already been processed several times.

00:08:49.291 --> 00:08:57.942
SPEAKER_00: In July 1985, Roger Boisjoli warned that a similar field-joint problem could lead to a catastrophe of the highest order.

00:08:57.922 --> 00:08:59.544
SPEAKER_00: including loss of human life.

00:09:00.566 --> 00:09:02.428
SPEAKER_00: That memo did not come from hindsight.

00:09:03.149 --> 00:09:06.515
SPEAKER_00: It came from inside the system, months before Challenger.

00:09:07.376 --> 00:09:11.163
SPEAKER_00: The data pattern was also stronger than the launch night comparison made it feel.

00:09:11.202 --> 00:09:19.996
SPEAKER_00: The full flight history showed that all four flights at 63 degrees Fahrenheit or below had O-ring thermal distress.

00:09:19.976 --> 00:09:26.326
SPEAKER_00: The pattern stopped short of predicting certain failure on every cold launch, but it gave cold decision level weight.

00:09:27.248 --> 00:09:29.412
SPEAKER_00: The way the data was framed mattered.

00:09:30.472 --> 00:09:37.563
SPEAKER_00: If the room looks only at flights where distress already appeared, the temperature pattern can seem debatable.

00:09:37.543 --> 00:09:58.725
SPEAKER_00: if the room sees the full flight history including flights with no distress the cold weather signal becomes harder to treat as noise the framing changed what kind of warning the data became feinman's appendix named the broader danger a risk flown before without catastrophe can start to look safer than it is

00:09:58.705 --> 00:10:04.673
SPEAKER_00: A survived flight can show that the vehicle got through while saying little about whether the risk is safe to repeat.

00:10:05.654 --> 00:10:21.878
SPEAKER_00: By January 1986, the program had evidence of damage, a temperature concern, a launch constraint, repeated waivers, a warning memo, and a pattern that was easier to see when the full history was placed in one frame.

00:10:23.360 --> 00:10:28.317
SPEAKER_00: By January 1986, the warning was part of the way the program kept flying.

00:10:29.561 --> 00:10:34.938
SPEAKER_00: On January 27, the forecast turned the old joint problem into a launch decision.

00:10:36.116 --> 00:10:37.879
SPEAKER_00: Around 5.45 p.m.

00:10:37.960 --> 00:10:40.825
SPEAKER_00: Eastern Time, the first teleconference began.

00:10:41.846 --> 00:10:46.794
SPEAKER_00: Theokol engineers were worried about low temperature and O-ring performance.

00:10:46.815 --> 00:10:57.192
SPEAKER_00: Later, around 8.45 p.m., the discussion resumed with charts and data about erosion, blow-by, tests, and prior experience.

00:10:58.354 --> 00:11:02.039
SPEAKER_00: This was not a casual objection made from outside the program.

00:11:02.121 --> 00:11:16.840
SPEAKER_00: It came from the contractor responsible for the solid rocket motors, from engineers close to the hardware, and from a record that already contained erosion, blow-by, a constraint, waivers, and temperature concern.

00:11:17.274 --> 00:11:22.741
SPEAKER_00: The charts mattered because they were the warning's last formal shape before the launch decision.

00:11:23.803 --> 00:11:25.466
SPEAKER_00: They carried pieces of the history.

00:11:26.386 --> 00:11:34.638
SPEAKER_00: Erosion, blow-by, subscale tests, static tests, and the experience base for prior launches.

00:11:35.759 --> 00:11:41.326
SPEAKER_00: But a chart can show real information and still fail if it does not make the decision standard clear.

00:11:42.488 --> 00:11:46.253
SPEAKER_00: The engineering concern was not simply that the weather felt cold.

00:11:46.333 --> 00:11:50.336
SPEAKER_00: The concern was that the forecast was below the database.

00:11:50.653 --> 00:11:54.638
SPEAKER_00: The joint was being asked to work outside the experience engineers could defend.

00:11:55.538 --> 00:11:57.080
SPEAKER_00: Boisjoli focused on timing.

00:11:57.860 --> 00:12:02.024
SPEAKER_00: Low temperature could affect the O-ring sealing function at the moment the joint needed to seal.

00:12:02.085 --> 00:12:07.730
SPEAKER_00: Theokal engineers initially recommended against launch below 53 degrees Fahrenheit.

00:12:08.410 --> 00:12:15.477
SPEAKER_00: That number mattered because it was tied to the lowest prior launch temperature in the relevant experience.

00:12:15.498 --> 00:12:18.500
SPEAKER_00: Challenger was expected to launch far below it.

00:12:18.480 --> 00:12:21.245
SPEAKER_00: NASA managers challenge the evidence.

00:12:21.264 --> 00:12:24.149
SPEAKER_00: In a technical review, challenge can be necessary.

00:12:25.091 --> 00:12:27.794
SPEAKER_00: The danger came from the standard that began to govern the room.

00:12:28.716 --> 00:12:34.085
SPEAKER_00: The question drifted from, show that this is safe to fly, toward prove that it will fail.

00:12:35.186 --> 00:12:37.769
SPEAKER_00: Engineering evidence often does not arrive as certainty.

00:12:38.610 --> 00:12:45.601
SPEAKER_00: It arrives as a margin that has gone missing, a trend that has become stronger, a condition that is outside experience.

00:12:45.667 --> 00:12:49.251
SPEAKER_00: If uncertainty blocks launch, the warning has force.

00:12:50.212 --> 00:12:54.038
SPEAKER_00: If uncertainty permits launch, the warning has to do something much harder.

00:12:54.979 --> 00:12:57.022
SPEAKER_00: Predict catastrophe in advance.

00:12:57.802 --> 00:12:59.485
SPEAKER_00: The engineers had evidence of risk.

00:13:00.166 --> 00:13:05.232
SPEAKER_00: They did not have a precise equation that converted temperature into certain loss of vehicle.

00:13:06.114 --> 00:13:07.755
SPEAKER_00: That absence became central.

00:13:08.576 --> 00:13:14.745
SPEAKER_00: The uncertainty that should have made launch harder instead made the no-launch case easier to challenge.

00:13:15.113 --> 00:13:17.279
SPEAKER_00: Lund later described the logic plainly.

00:13:17.299 --> 00:13:24.263
SPEAKER_00: They got into the mode of trying to prove the motor would not work, and they could not prove absolute failure.

00:13:25.265 --> 00:13:27.975
SPEAKER_00: That gap helped the launch case survive.

00:13:28.039 --> 00:13:29.863
SPEAKER_00: Theokol management took a caucus.

00:13:30.705 --> 00:13:34.510
SPEAKER_00: Inside that process came the phrase that still carries the decision's shape.

00:13:35.293 --> 00:13:38.418
SPEAKER_00: Take off the engineering hat and put on the management hat.

00:13:39.078 --> 00:13:40.240
SPEAKER_00: The same cold existed.

00:13:40.280 --> 00:13:42.083
SPEAKER_00: The same joint existed.

00:13:42.124 --> 00:13:44.368
SPEAKER_00: The same data limits existed.

00:13:45.190 --> 00:13:47.212
SPEAKER_00: But the judgment changed categories.

00:13:48.375 --> 00:13:52.883
SPEAKER_00: Around 11 p.m., Theokol reversed and recommended launch.

00:13:53.200 --> 00:14:00.863
SPEAKER_00: The final recommendation looked like process, a contractor position, charts, managers, and a conclusion.

00:14:01.846 --> 00:14:06.720
SPEAKER_00: It no longer carried the engineering refusal that made the warning operational.

00:14:06.835 --> 00:14:10.240
SPEAKER_00: No single phrase or person explains the disaster.

00:14:10.260 --> 00:14:17.193
SPEAKER_00: The meeting chain could take a specific engineering objection and return a launch recommendation from the same process.

00:14:18.195 --> 00:14:24.186
SPEAKER_00: The launch eve reversal is dramatic, but it is not the whole system failure.

00:14:24.166 --> 00:14:31.113
SPEAKER_00: The Commission found that higher-level launch decision-makers did not receive the full warning in the form they needed.

00:14:32.153 --> 00:14:35.236
SPEAKER_00: They did not know the recent O-ring history with enough clarity.

00:14:36.138 --> 00:14:43.264
SPEAKER_00: They did not know that Thiokol had initially made a written recommendation against launch below 53 degrees Fahrenheit.

00:14:44.265 --> 00:14:50.292
SPEAKER_00: They did not know that engineering opposition continued after Thiokol management changed its position.

00:14:50.272 --> 00:15:19.738
SPEAKER_00: a warning also has to travel it has to move from hardware to engineers from engineers to managers from contractors to nasa from lower review levels to the people with authority to stop the launch at each step the signal can be compressed compression is normal in large programs but when compression changes an active objection into a resolved item the system has changed the decision without saying so directly

00:15:19.717 --> 00:15:43.953
SPEAKER_00: level one and level two management did not receive the concern with the full shape the record deserved the issue was not just there had been o-ring concern the issue was the combination prior distress cold sensitivity the 53 degrees fahrenheit engineering floor continuing engineer opposition and a launch morning outside the defended experience base

00:15:44.929 --> 00:15:53.184
SPEAKER_00: Safety should have been a backstop, but no safety or reliability representative was invited to the January 27th teleconference.

00:15:54.086 --> 00:16:01.099
SPEAKER_00: No safety representative sat on the mission management team during key countdown decisions on January 28th.

00:16:01.078 --> 00:16:12.014
SPEAKER_00: The Commission also criticized weak problem reporting, inadequate trend analysis, misrepresented criticality, and lack of involvement in critical discussions.

00:16:13.115 --> 00:16:18.823
SPEAKER_00: Safety appeared in values and documents at the decisive points it lacked independent structure.

00:16:19.806 --> 00:16:30.039
SPEAKER_00: People can care about safety while the way decisions actually get made still allows a warning to arrive too late, too thin, or too resolved to change action.

00:16:30.019 --> 00:16:36.047
SPEAKER_00: The phrase silent safety is useful because it avoids the easy moral shortcut.

00:16:36.820 --> 00:16:39.583
SPEAKER_00: The problem was not that safety was never mentioned.

00:16:40.325 --> 00:16:45.192
SPEAKER_00: The problem was that safety did not have enough independent presence at the decisive points.

00:16:46.234 --> 00:16:48.397
SPEAKER_00: It did not force the full trend into view.

00:16:48.456 --> 00:16:53.403
SPEAKER_00: It did not make the original engineering objection unavoidable for the final launch authority.

00:16:54.346 --> 00:17:05.561
SPEAKER_00: By launch morning, the warning had passed through hardware evidence, paperwork, waivers, charts, recommendation, caucus, and management acceptance.

00:17:06.165 --> 00:17:09.015
SPEAKER_00: At the end of that route, launch was still open.

00:17:10.239 --> 00:17:12.265
SPEAKER_00: At 11.38 a.m.

00:17:12.486 --> 00:17:19.347
SPEAKER_00: ET on January 28, 1986, the solid rocket boosters ignited.

00:17:19.784 --> 00:17:24.353
SPEAKER_00: The right aft field joint was in the coldest conditions the shuttle program had accepted.

00:17:25.394 --> 00:17:28.641
SPEAKER_00: Within the first second, smoke appeared near that joint.

00:17:29.623 --> 00:17:33.569
SPEAKER_00: The primary O-ring seal had not contained the gases the way it needed to.

00:17:34.771 --> 00:17:38.098
SPEAKER_00: The smoke continued through T plus 2.500.

00:17:39.260 --> 00:17:41.505
SPEAKER_00: Then it disappeared.

00:17:41.653 --> 00:17:45.901
SPEAKER_00: The commission considered that combustion residue may have temporarily sealed the breach.

00:17:46.741 --> 00:17:51.609
SPEAKER_00: For a short time, the vehicle could look normal, while the failure chain remained alive.

00:17:52.731 --> 00:17:56.057
SPEAKER_00: That temporary quiet is one of the cruelest details in the record.

00:17:56.837 --> 00:18:02.446
SPEAKER_00: The system had a visible sign of breach, then a period of apparent normal flight.

00:18:02.561 --> 00:18:05.185
SPEAKER_00: The same pattern had been playing out administratively.

00:18:05.887 --> 00:18:06.709
SPEAKER_00: Damage appears.

00:18:07.309 --> 00:18:08.432
SPEAKER_00: Explanation arrives.

00:18:09.133 --> 00:18:10.075
SPEAKER_00: Flight continues.

00:18:11.076 --> 00:18:16.645
SPEAKER_00: The opening smoke matters because the disaster did not begin when the television image changed.

00:18:17.607 --> 00:18:22.596
SPEAKER_00: The physical failure had begun at ignition, then hit itself.

00:18:22.576 --> 00:18:26.547
SPEAKER_00: Around 58 to 60 seconds into flight, flame became visible.

00:18:27.470 --> 00:18:33.145
SPEAKER_00: Hot gas from the right booster began damaging surrounding structure, including the external tank area.

00:18:33.165 --> 00:18:37.377
SPEAKER_00: The hidden breach had become visible consequence.

00:18:38.167 --> 00:18:41.273
SPEAKER_00: At about 73 seconds, Challenger broke apart.

00:18:42.175 --> 00:18:52.676
SPEAKER_00: Francis Scobie, Michael Smith, Judith Resnick, Ellison Onizuka, Ronald McNair, Gregory Jarvis, and Krista McAuliffe were lost.

00:18:53.759 --> 00:18:56.463
SPEAKER_00: The facts do not need extra drama.

00:18:56.443 --> 00:18:59.894
SPEAKER_00: The physical cause was a failed seal in a cold field joint.

00:19:00.657 --> 00:19:05.694
SPEAKER_00: The system cause was a warning that moved through the organization without keeping enough force to stop launch.

00:19:06.577 --> 00:19:09.406
SPEAKER_00: Challenger is often reduced to cold weather in O-rings.

00:19:10.113 --> 00:19:12.915
SPEAKER_00: The sharper pattern is how danger changed categories.

00:19:13.836 --> 00:19:15.558
SPEAKER_00: O-ring damage became an anomaly.

00:19:16.259 --> 00:19:18.902
SPEAKER_00: An anomaly became accepted risk.

00:19:18.922 --> 00:19:21.064
SPEAKER_00: Accepted risk became a launch constraint.

00:19:21.845 --> 00:19:23.626
SPEAKER_00: A launch constraint became a waiver.

00:19:24.367 --> 00:19:25.808
SPEAKER_00: A waiver became precedent.

00:19:26.549 --> 00:19:28.971
SPEAKER_00: Precedent became confidence.

00:19:28.991 --> 00:19:32.556
SPEAKER_00: The shuttle system also faced flight rate and resource pressure.

00:19:33.436 --> 00:19:39.343
SPEAKER_00: The commission described a program stretched by the attempt to fly often and operate routinely.

00:19:39.442 --> 00:19:42.005
SPEAKER_00: Rapid cadence made anomaly analysis harder.

00:19:42.644 --> 00:19:46.288
SPEAKER_00: Information from one flight could arrive too late to shape the next formal review.

00:19:47.150 --> 00:19:50.614
SPEAKER_00: STS61C is part of that context.

00:19:51.434 --> 00:19:58.000
SPEAKER_00: Post-flight O-ring information from the January flight was not available in time for the formal 51L review.

00:19:58.040 --> 00:20:01.005
SPEAKER_00: That does not make cadence the only cause.

00:20:01.785 --> 00:20:08.132
SPEAKER_00: It shows how a fast operating rhythm can reduce the time available for warnings to become decisions.

00:20:08.617 --> 00:20:12.243
SPEAKER_00: The program had started treating routine flight as the goal.

00:20:13.165 --> 00:20:18.335
SPEAKER_00: That expectation met a booster joint record that still looked like an unresolved development problem.

00:20:19.036 --> 00:20:24.025
SPEAKER_00: When an organization wants routine operation, unresolved warnings create friction.

00:20:24.065 --> 00:20:30.536
SPEAKER_00: The friction can be handled by stopping or it can be handled by making the warning easier to carry.

00:20:31.877 --> 00:20:34.001
SPEAKER_00: That pressure matters.

00:20:33.981 --> 00:20:42.930
SPEAKER_00: But the record does not support the easy folklore that outside political pressure or a State of the Union deadline caused the launch decision.

00:20:44.151 --> 00:20:48.294
SPEAKER_00: The stronger explanation is internal and more useful.

00:20:49.115 --> 00:20:57.942
SPEAKER_00: The program had built enough momentum, process, and confidence to keep a known risk moving through the normal work of launch.

00:20:57.962 --> 00:21:00.125
SPEAKER_00: That sequence is warning softening.

00:21:00.924 --> 00:21:03.988
SPEAKER_00: A system does not have to forget danger to become vulnerable.

00:21:03.968 --> 00:21:07.952
SPEAKER_00: It can remember danger in a form that no longer controls behavior.

00:21:07.992 --> 00:21:13.641
SPEAKER_00: The next case, Therac-25, changes the mechanism.

00:21:14.662 --> 00:21:19.449
SPEAKER_00: Trust accumulates around a machine until trust itself becomes part of the hazard.

00:21:20.470 --> 00:21:23.213
SPEAKER_00: Challenger leaves the starting point for that question.

00:21:24.234 --> 00:21:29.082
SPEAKER_00: How a system changes before consequence makes the change impossible to ignore.
